        <body>
            <head><name type="stone">CIIC 100. <placeName type="townland">Ballyhank</placeName> 
                    IV</name>, Co. <placeName type="county">Cork</placeName></head>
            <ab><rs>National Monuments Service Record Number: <ref
                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=CO085-067006-"
                >CO085-067006-</ref>
                </rs></ab>
            <div type="description" n="site type">
                <head>Site Type</head>
                <p>Souterrain</p>
            </div>
            <div type="description">
                <head>Description</head>
                <div type="description" n="site">
                    <head>Site</head>
                    <p>A souterrain (CO085-067002-) in the SW quadrant of a ringfort (CO085-067001-).
                        <q>The souterrain was a passage 52' long, in three sections, 18', 16' and 18'
                            long respectively, on a slight zig-zag plan and with no expansion at
                            either end</q>
                        <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"><bibl>(<author>Macalister</author>
                                <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >92-3</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="monument">
                    <head>Monument</head>
                    <p>1 of 6 Ogam stones re-used in the construction of a souterrain. <rs
                            type="material">Clayslate</rs>, <rs type="dimensions">
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="height">1.3</measure>m x
                                <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="width">0.6</measure>m x
                                <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="depth">0.2</measure>m
                            (converted from <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                                        ><bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                    <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >97</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div type="description" n="text">
                    <head>Text</head>
                    <p>Inscription <rs type="execution">cut</rs> on one angle, up.</p>
                    <p><q>The <foreign xml:lang="ga">AB</foreign> which <name type="author"
                                >Macalister</name> reads some distance before the name <persName
                                xml:lang="ga">ULCCAGNI</persName> is not very deeply cut and there
                            is ground for considerable doubt as to whether it should be considered
                            part of the inscription</q>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author>
                                <date>1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">66</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>
                        .</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="ga">
                <head xml:lang="en">Transliteration</head>
                <ab>
                    <lb/>
                    <w>AB</w><space></space>
                    <persName><w lemma="ULCCAGNI">ULCCAG<unclear reason="damage">N</unclear>I</w></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <head>Translation</head>
                <p><q>? of <persName>Olc√°n</persName></q></p>
            </div>
            <div type="figure">
                <head>Images</head>
                <div type="figure" n="three-dimensional-model">
                    <head>3D model</head>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="photographs">
                    <head>Photographs</head>
                                   </div>
                <div type="figure" n="drawings">
                    <head>Drawings</head>
                                    </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p><ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                        ><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                            (<date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >97</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> interprets AB as 'Abbot', but <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1991"><bibl><author>McManus</author> 
                                    (<date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >61</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> sugests that the AB 'is best ignored.'</p></item>
                    <item n="2"><p><foreign xml:lang="ga"><hi rend="italic">Olc</hi></foreign> 
                        '<gloss>evil</gloss>' and diminutive suffix <foreign>-<hi
                            rend="italic">agni</hi> (>-<hi rend="italic"
                                >an(n)</hi>)</foreign>, cp. <name type="stone">467. <placeName
                                    type="findspot">Lewannick</placeName> II</name>,
                        <placeName>Cornwall</placeName> (<foreign xml:lang="ga"
                            >ULCAGNI</foreign> with single C, also Latin inscription: <foreign
                                xml:lang="la">VLCAGNI</foreign>) and a further British inscription
                        in Latin only (370. <foreign xml:lang="la">VLCAGNVS</foreign> - in nom.
                        after <foreign xml:lang="la">HIC IACIT</foreign>, dating from the
                        <origDate notBefore="0450" notAfter="0500">latter part of 5th century</origDate> 
                        following Jackson's chronology of British inscriptions <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author>
                            <date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >64, 97</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. Old Irish <foreign xml:lang="ga"><hi rend="italic"
                                    >olc/luch</hi></foreign> reflex of Indo-European word for
                        '<gloss>wolf</gloss>' <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCC1985"
                            >(<bibl><author>McCone</author>
                                <date when="1985">1985</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >171-6</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p></item>
                </list>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">In souterrain with 5 other Ogham stones in <placeName
                                type="townland">Ballyhank</placeName>, barony of <placeName
                                type="barony">East Muskerry</placeName>. (GPS coordinates
                                <geo>-8.609923,51.831600</geo>)  </rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Unknown</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation"><orgName>National Museum of Ireland</orgName> (<idno>NMI Ref. 1872:21</idno>), 
                                <placeName type="county">Dublin</placeName>. The present location of
                            this stone may be accessed via the <ref
                                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=DU018-372----"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                                www.archaeology.ie</ref>. (GPS coordinates
                                <geo>-6.254558,53.340408</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head>History of Recording</head>
                <p>Discovered by <placeName type="county">Cork</placeName> antiquaries <persName
                        type="surname">Windele</persName>, <persName type="surname">Abell</persName>
                    and <persName type="surname">Hawkes</persName> in <date when="1846">1846</date>.
                    <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                        ><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                            (<date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >92-3</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> records the removal of all ogham stones from their
                    original location in the Ballyhank souterrain, <q>one of these was purchased from
                    the local farmer by F. M. Jennings in 1846, and presented by him to the Royal
                    Irish Academy (PRIA 3: 213, without any statement of provenance): in 1849
                    Windele removed the remaining stones to his own residence</q>. All six were later re-united in the National Museum of Ireland collection. </p>
            </div>
